## v1.3.0 (2026-06-30) — class-level #1462
**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1462 — produce (and REVISE after a NOGO) an
implementation plan to decompose the 2103-line `CIDriver` god **CLASS** (6 methods over the
80-line cap).

**Verification:** unverified (planning-phase learnings; no code ran end-to-end). The honesty
gate is honored — the class-level workflow is titled "Proposed Workflow" with the UNVERIFIED
warning banner.

**What changed (minor bump 1.2.0 → 1.3.0 — additive; the function-level core v1.0.0–v1.2.0
workflow is unchanged):**

- Extended scope from god-FUNCTION extraction to god-CLASS / collaborator extraction. Added
  two new "When to Use" triggers (5, 6) for class decomposition and the intra-helper-vs-
  collaborator decision.
- Added a "God-CLASS Decomposition" section with a **Proposed Workflow** decision tree
  (STEP 0 seam-count → STEP 1 AST-measure/RED cap-test → STEP 2 helper-vs-collaborator →
  STEP 3 delegation-stub + injected providers → **STEP 3a circular-import check** → STEP 4
  whole-test-tree seam sweep).
- **Risk 10a (the #1 learning — earned the NOGO): "Circular import when extracting a
  collaborator — relocate shared helpers to a cycle-free leaf + re-export."** When the moved
  method body uses a module-level helper defined in the god module (here
  `_without_auto_merge_policy` + `_AUTO_MERGE_POLICY_CHECK` in `ci_driver.py`), a top-level
  back-import from the collaborator creates a genuine `god → collaborator → god` cycle. Fix:
  relocate the stateless helper to a cycle-free leaf (`ci_check_inspector.py`, verified leaf
  via `grep "from .ci_driver"` → no match), re-export from the god module via the
  `name as name` alias idiom (no `# ruff: noqa: F401`; RUF100 guard), and import it into the
  collaborator FROM THE LEAF — mirroring the `FAILING_CHECK_CONCLUSIONS` #1357 precedent.
  Detection rule: enumerate every MODULE-LEVEL symbol the moved body references (not just
  `self._` calls) and verify with
  `python -c "import god_module; import new_module; print('no cycle')"`.
- **Risk 10: patch.object seam preservation is the dominant class-decomposition constraint**
  (296 `patch.object(driver, ...)` sites in `test_ci_driver.py`); every extracted method keeps
  a 3-line delegation stub on the original class with lambda providers injected in `__init__`
  so each seam still intercepts at call time.
- **Risk 11: intra-class helper vs injected-provider collaborator — decide by sibling
  `self._` call count.** Many sibling calls → intra-class private helper (small provider
  surface; KISS/YAGNI). Few external sibling calls + cohesive sub-responsibility (e.g. an
  "arming state machine") → new injected-provider collaborator.
- **Risk 12: unverified class-decomposition reliances the reviewer must re-check** (eyeballed
  helper line counts; whole-test-tree internal-name patch sweep; injected-lambda signature
  re-read on disk; import-boundary tests; verbatim control-flow body diff; RED cap-test
  enumerating the TRUE over-cap set; extracted poll loop must RETURN the data the caller
  recomputes — `_poll_post_fix_ci` returns the `checks` list, not a bool, preserving the
  caller's pass/fail evaluation at `ci_driver.py:888`).
- Added 4 `## Failed Attempts` rows: (a) the naive top-level back-import that creates the
  cycle (the NOGO); (b) extracting every over-cap method into a collaborator (wide provider
  surface, KISS/YAGNI); (c) writing an injected-lambda signature without re-reading the real
  method; (d) eyeballing helper line counts from block boundaries.
- Added god-class items to the planning checklist (including the circular-import check).
- Extended `description:` and added tags `god-class`, `collaborator-extraction`,
  `patch-object-seams`, `delegation-stub`, `injected-provider`, `srp`, `circular-import`,
  `import-cycle`, `leaf-module`, `re-export`.
- Bumped `version:` 1.2.0 → 1.3.0; `date:` → 2026-06-30.

**Why:** Producing the #1462 plan surfaced a failure mode neither
`architecture-god-function-decomposition-planning-risks` (function-scoped) nor
`automation-god-package-shim-first-decomposition` captured: the circular import when a
collaborator extracted from a god class back-imports a module-level helper from that class.
The plan took a NOGO until the helper was relocated to a cycle-free leaf and re-exported. The
class-vs-function decomposition decision criterion (sibling-`self._`-call count) and the
patch-seam-count-as-risk-metric are likewise new to this skill.

